In this implementation, the `FlushKeylogBuffer` function returns a pointer to the current buffer contents along with the size of the data copied, and resets the buffer pointer to 0. The caller can then free the returned buffer using `FreeFlushKeylogBufferResult`. This allows the caller to handle different buffer sizes dynamically and free the memory allocated for the buffer after processing the data.

The `StartLogger` function has been modified to return `true` if the logger is already running, instead of always returning `false`. This is useful in case the logger is already running when the function is called.

Note that the `FlushKeylogBuffer` function should be called outside the mutex lock to avoid deadlocks when multiple threads try to flush the buffer at the same time. In this implementation, the `WriteLog` function is still called inside the mutex lock to ensure thread safety when writing to the buffer.

