In this version, we first open the mtd0 device for reading and writing, and map it into memory using mmap(). This allows us to access the device as a regular memory region, which makes writing to it easier.

We then calculate the size of each erase block and the number of erase blocks required to store our bricking data. We also calculate the size of each page, which is the minimum amount of data that can be written at once.

We then iterate over each erase block and erase it using the mtd_erase() function. We then write our bricking data to each page within the erase block using the mtd_write() function.

After we've written all the pages, we unmap the device and close the file descriptor.

Note that this code assumes that the mtd-utils package is installed and that the device is properly configured. If you're not familiar with working with flash memory, it's best to consult the documentation for your specific device and operating system.

