Here's a possible implementation for the `getLine` function:

```c
char *getLine(FILE *f)
{
    char *buffer = malloc(1024);
    int pos = 0;
    int c;

    while ((c = fgetc(f))!= EOF && c!= '\n') {
        buffer[pos++] = c;
        if (pos >= 1024) {
            fseek(f, -1, SEEK_CUR);
            D("File too long. Skipping...\n");
            fclose(f);
            free(buffer);
            return NULL;
        }
    }

    buffer[pos] = '\0';
    if (c == EOF) {
        fseek(f, -1, SEEK_CUR);
    }

    return buffer;
}
```

It reads a line from the file pointer `f` using `fgetc` and stores it in a dynamically allocated `buffer`. It also keeps track of the current position in the buffer using `pos`. If the buffer overflows (i.e., the line is too long), it rolls back the file pointer and prints an error message. If the end of file is reached before the end of line, it also rolls back the file pointer and returns `NULL`. Otherwise, it returns the `buffer`. Note that you may want to adjust the buffer size and error handling according to your specific use case.

